sectionBreak.stem:
The following data represent the bacterial growth in a liquid culture over a number of days:

 

Day 0 4 8 12 16 20
Amount ×106 67.38 74.67 82.74 91.69 101.60 112.58

internal_category.title: Topic: General Linear Least-Squares and Nonlinear Regression
ABET Outcomes: (a) an ability to apply knowledge of mathematics, science, and engineering
Chapter: 15 General Linear Least-Squares and Nonlinear Regression

property.name: commonFeedback
property.value:
The following script can be developed to solve this problem:

 

clear,clc,clf,format short g
format compact
t = [0 4 8 12 16 20]'; B = [67.38 74.67 82.74 91.69 101.60 112.58]';
disp('linear:')
Z=[ones(size(t)) t];
a=(Z'*Z)\(Z'*B);a'
Sr=sum((B-Z*a).^2);
r2=1-Sr/sum((B-mean(B)).^2)
syx=sqrt(Sr/(length(B)-length(a)))
tp=[0:35];
Bplin=a(1)+a(2)*tp;
Bp35lin=a(1)+a(2)*35;
pause
disp('parabolic:')
Z=[ones(size(t)) t t.^2];
a=(Z'*Z)\(Z'*B);a'
Sr=sum((B-Z*a).^2);
r2=1-Sr/sum((B-mean(B)).^2)
syx=sqrt(Sr/(length(B)-length(a)))
tp=[0:35];
Bpquad=a(1)+a(2)*tp+a(3)*tp.^2;
Bp35quad=a(1)+a(2)*35+a(3)*35^2;
pause
disp('exponential:')
Z=[ones(size(t)) t];
a=(Z'*Z)\(Z'*log(B));a'
Sr=sum((log(B)-Z*a).^2);
r2=1-Sr/sum((log(B)-mean(log(B))).^2)
syx=sqrt(Sr/(length(log(B))-length(a)))
tp=[0:35];
Bpexp=exp(a(1)+a(2)*tp);
Bp35exp=exp(a(1)+a(2)*35);
Bp35lin
Bp35quad
Bp35exp
plot(t,B,'o',tp,Bplin,tp,Bpquad,tp,Bpexp)
legend('data','linear','quadratic','exponential','location','Best')
 

Output

 

linear:
ans =
        65.89       2.2553
r2 =
      0.99445
syx =
       1.4095
parabolic:
ans =
  Columns 1 through 2
       67.427       1.6792
  Column 3
     0.028806
r2 =
      0.99999
syx =
     0.072757
exponential:
ans =
       4.2104     0.025666
r2 =
            1
syx =
   3.6082e-05
Bp35lin =
       144.83
Bp35quad =
       161.48
Bp35exp =
       165.45

 

%media:15.016.1.jpg%

 

The linear model is inadequate since it does not capture the curving trend of the data. At face value, the parabolic and exponential models appear to be equally good. However, inspection of the standard error of the estimate indicates that the exponential model is somewhat better. In addition, knowledge of bacterial growth might lead you to choose the exponential model as it is commonly used to simulate the growth of microorganism populations. Interestingly, the choice matters when the models are used for prediction. If the exponential model is used, the result is as follows:

 

%media:formula5.mml%

worksheet.stem:
Three disease-carrying organisms decay exponentially in lake water according to the following model:

 

%media:formula8.mml%

 

Use nonlinear regression to estimate the initial population of each organism (A, B, and C) given the following measurements:

 

t, hr 0.5 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 9
p(t) 6.0 4.4 3.2 2.7 2.2 1.9 1.7 1.4 1.1

 

(Round the final answers to four decimal places.)

 

The initial population of organism A = __a__, B = __b__, and C = __c__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Nonlinear regression can be used to evaluate the coefficients. First, a function can be set up to compute the sum of the squares of the residuals.

 

function f = fSSR1528(a,t,pm)
pp=a(1)*exp(-1.5*t)+a(2)*exp(-0.3*t)+a(3)*exp(-0.05*t);
f = sum((pm-pp).^2);

 

Then, the fminsearch function can be employed to determine the coefficients.

 

clear,clc,clf,format short g
t=[0.5 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 9];
p=[6.0 4.4 3.2 2.7 2.2 1.9 1.7 1.4 1.1];
a=fminsearch(@fSSR1528,[1 1 1],[],t,p)
tp=[0:0.1:10];
pp=a(1)*exp(-1.5*tp)+a(2)*exp(-0.3*tp)+a(3)*exp(-0.05*tp);
plot(t,p,'o',tp,pp)
xlabel('t'),ylabel('p')

 

Output

 

a =
       4.0046       2.9213       1.5647

 

%media:15.028.jpg%

 

Therefore, A = 4.0046, B = 2.9213, and C = 1.5647.

worksheet.stem:
The Antoine equation describes the relation between vapor pressure and temperature for pure components as


%media:formula10.mml%


where p is the vapor pressure, T is temperature (K), and A, B, and C are component-specific constants.

Consider the following measurements:

 

T K 50 60 70 80 90 100 110 120 130
p (Pa) 82 2300 18500 80500 2.3 × 105 5 × 105 9.6 × 105 1.5 × 106 2.4 × 106

 

Use MATLAB to determine the best values for the constants for carbon monoxide based on the given measurements. Also, determine the r2 and sy∕x for your fit. (Round the final answers to three decimal places.)

 

The best values are as follows:

A = __a__

B = __b__

C = __c__

The value of r2 = __d__ and sy/x = __e__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Function

 

function f = fSSR29(a,T,lnP)
lnPA = a(1) - a(2)./(a(3)+T);
f = sum((lnPA-lnP).^2);

 

Script

 

clear,clc,clf,format short g,format compact
TC=[50 60 70 80 90 100 110 120 130];
p=[82 2300 18500 80500 2.3e5 5e5 9.6e5 1.5e6 2.4e6];
lnp=log(p);
TK=TC+273.15;
aguess=[20 500 -200];
a = fminsearch(@fSSR29, aguess, [], TK,lnp)
% fit stats
TK=TC+273.15;
lnpred = a(1) - a(2)./(a(3)+TK);
SSR = sum((lnp - lnpred).^2)
SST = sum((lnp - mean(lnp)).^2)
r2 = (SST - SSR)/SST
r = sqrt(r2)
syx = sqrt(SSR/(length(lnp)-3))
% plot
Tp=linspace(min(TC),max(TC));
TKA=Tp+273.15;
lnpA = a(1) - a(2)./(a(3)+TKA);
plot(TC,lnp,'o',Tp,lnpA)

 

Output

       19.003        491.7      -289.47
SSR =
    0.0030002
SST =
       92.922
r2 =
      0.99997
r =
      0.99998
syx =
     0.022362

hint.name: hint #1
hint.value: Which MATLAB function is used to find k20 and θ?

worksheet.stem:
Use a transformation to linearize the given equation and then employ linear regression to estimate k20 and θ. Also, employ the equation to predict the reaction rate at T = 17 °C. (Round the final answers to four decimal places.)

 

The value of k20 = __a__ and θ = __b__.

The reaction rate at T = 17 °C is __c__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Function

 

function f = fSSR(a,Td,kd)
km = a(1)*a(2).^(Td-20);
f = sum((km-kd).^2);

 

Script


clear,clc,clf,format short g,format compact
Td=[6 12 18 24 30];
kd=[0.15 0.20 0.32 0.45 0.70];
% linear fit
logkd=log10(kd); Tdminus20=Td-20;
al=polyfit(Tdminus20,logkd,1)
kdl=10^al(2),thetal=10^al(1)
k17l=kdl*thetal^(17-20)
Tp=linspace(0,max(Td));
kpl = kdl*thetal.^(Tp-20);
plot(Td,kd,'o',Tp,kpl)
legend('data','linear','nonlinear','location','best')

 

Output

 

al =
      0.02817     -0.44754
kdl =
      0.35683
thetal =
        1.067
k17l =
      0.29373
